pub const INTRO_BASE: &str = "Welcome to Off Script! You’re about to play a game of subtle clues, quick thinking, and a little bit of bluffing.\n\nEveryone but one of you has the same prompt.\nOne player — the impostor — has something different.\n\nTake turns asking questions about the prompt.\nAfter each question, everyone else gives an answer. Keep things natural — don’t reveal too much.\n\nIf you have the real prompt, your goal is to spot who doesn’t quite fit.\nIf you’re the impostor, your goal is to blend in and figure out what everyone else is talking about.\n\nOnce everyone has asked a question, vote on who you think the impostor is.\n\nStay subtle. Stay convincing.\nAnd whatever you do… don’t go off script.";

pub const BOT_INTRO_BASE: &str = "Game: Off Script. There are N players, and one player is randomly assigned as the impostor. All other players receive the same prompt, while the impostor receives a different but related prompt. The game proceeds in a single round where each player asks exactly one question about the prompt, and after each question, all other players answer based on their own prompt. Answers should be truthful but indirect, avoiding explicit keywords or obvious giveaways. Strategy: Questions should be open-ended and designed to reveal differences in interpretation rather than surface details. Avoid yes/no questions. Good questions probe dimensions like context, tone, typical scenarios, or personal experiences that would naturally differ between similar prompts. Do not ask questions that would make the prompt obvious if answered directly. When answering, provide responses that are specific enough to be believable, but general enough to apply to closely related prompts. Avoid extreme or highly distinctive details unless they are very common. Pay attention to patterns across multiple answers rather than any single response. As a non-impostor, aim to identify subtle inconsistencies in how others interpret the prompt, especially across multiple questions. Ask questions that force players to commit to details that may conflict later. As the impostor, infer the true prompt by identifying common themes in others’ answers. Mirror the level of specificity and tone used by others, and prefer safe, broadly applicable answers early on. Gradually refine your answers as you gather more information, but avoid sudden shifts in interpretation that could draw suspicion. After all players have asked one question, all players vote on who they believe the impostor is.";
